    {
      "title": "Transitive and Intransitive Verbs",
      "titleArabic": "الفعل اللازم والمتعدي",
      "content": [
        "Intransitive verbs can be made transitive by doubling the second radical (Form II) or prefixing hamza (Form IV). This change often adds causative meaning."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Intransitive: خَرَجَ (to go out)",
        "Transitive Form IV: أَخْرَجَ (to take out)",
        "Transitive Form II: خَرَّجَ (to graduate someone)",
        "Form II often indicates intensive or extensive action"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "فَرِحَ - فَرَّحَ - أَفْرَحَ", "english": "to be happy - to make happy (intensively) - to make happy" },
        { "arabic": "عَلِمَ - عَلَّمَ - أَعْلَمَ", "english": "to know - to teach - to inform" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Object of Purpose (المفعول لأجله)",
      "titleArabic": "المفعول لأجله",
      "content": [
        "The maf'ūl lahu (object of purpose) is a maṣdar indicating the reason or purpose for the action. It answers the question 'why?' and is always in the accusative case."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Must be a maṣdar (verbal noun)",
        "Indicates reason for the action",
        "Always manṣūb (accusative)",
        "Can be replaced by لِ + noun phrase"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "جِئْتُ طَلَبًا لِلْعِلْمِ", "english": "I came seeking knowledge" },
        { "arabic": "هَرَبَ خَوْفًا مِنَ الْعَدُوِّ", "english": "He fled out of fear of the enemy" },
        { "arabic": "سَافَرَ رَغْبَةً فِي النَّجَاحِ", "english": "He traveled out of desire for success" }
      ]
    }
